Got it 👍 You don’t need a separate utility class, just a single method inside your service or resolver.
Here’s a simple generic method that checks required fields and throws if any are missing:

private void validateMandatoryFields(Map<String, ?> fields) {
    List<String> missing = new ArrayList<>();

    for (Map.Entry<String, ?> entry : fields.entrySet()) {
        String name = entry.getKey();
        Object val  = entry.getValue();

        boolean invalid = (val == null) ||
                          (val instanceof CharSequence && ((CharSequence) val).toString().trim().isEmpty());

        if (invalid) {
            missing.add(name);
        }
    }

    if (!missing.isEmpty()) {
        String msg = "Missing or blank mandatory fields: " + String.join(", ", missing);
        logger.error(msg); // use your logger
        throw new CustomValidationException(msg);
    }
}


⸻

Example usage:

validateMandatoryFields(Map.of(
    "notificationType", notificationType,
    "triggerType",      triggerType,
    "messageType",      messageType,
    "language",         language,
    "agencyNumber",     agencyNumber
));


